<paragraph id="E97036DD3F66FFF1FF76FEA4FDD6FEDD" blockId="83.[151,1437,290,964]" box="[151,566,290,317]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
Size. Attains about 
<quantity id="2E379B383F66FFF1FE90FEA4FE48FEDD" box="[369,424,290,317]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F66FFF1FF26FEC0FB60FC25" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F66FFF1FF26FEC0FE63FDD9" blockId="83.[151,1437,290,964]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
Morphology. D VI + I,9–11; A I,11–12; P 13–15. Body elongate, its depth 6.0–7.0 in standard length. Head with short snout. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F66FFF1FEC2FEECFB31FE65" bold="true" box="[291,1233,361,388]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Eyes dorsolateral, about upper one-third elevated above dorsal profile of head</emphasis>
. Caudal peduncle slender, lower than body depth. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F66FFF1FE16FE0BFD60FE2D" bold="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">First dorsal fin higher than second fin, the first spine longest, slightly prolonged in males, giving the fin a triangular shape</emphasis>
. Pelvic fins united to form a disc, reaching origin of anal fin. Caudal fin rounded, slightly shorter than head. Scales on body ctenoid, no scales on head, nape, and prepectoral and prepelvic areas. Scales visible on dead specimens from reticulate pattern of pigmentation along scale edges, visibility on live specimens unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F66FFF1FF26FDC4FC64FCF1" blockId="83.[151,1437,290,964]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
Freshly dead coloration. Finely mottled light brown dorsally, grading to white ventrally on head and abdomen, with 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F66FFF1FF31FDE0FB84FD61" bold="true" box="[208,1124,613,640]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">a midlateral series of 9–10 gray to blackish blotches about eye size or smaller</emphasis>
, the first 2 beneath pectoral fin and the last on caudal-fin base, the penultimate being the smallest; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F66FFF1FC5EFD0CFD7DFD26" bold="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">most of these blotches are bisected by a vertical, slightly curved, brown-orange line</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F66FFF1FD4DFD28FCE1FD29" box="[684,769,686,712]" captionStart="FIGURE 72" captionStartId="83.[151,250,1699,1723]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,988,1676]" captionTargetId="figure-345@83.[151,1435,988,1676]" captionTargetPageId="83" captionText="FIGURE 72. Freshly dead coloration of Silhouettea aegyptia. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Al Lith, Saudi Arabia, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601779" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601779/files/figure.png" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
). A series of similar curved lines below the midlateral row; scattered shorter brownish yellow dashes dorsally. First dorsal fin with three oblique dark crossbands; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F66FFF1FAA6FD54FC9EFCF1" bold="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">rays of dorsal three-fourths of caudal fin with aligned small dark dots</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F66FFF1FF26FC9CFCACFCD5" blockId="83.[151,1437,290,964]" box="[199,844,794,820]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F66FFF1FE9EFC9CFD5FFCD5" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1810" box="[383,703,794,820]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Pomatoschistus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marmoratus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F66FFF1FE9EFC9CFD5FFCD5" box="[383,703,794,820]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Pomatoschistus marmoratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F66FFF1FD2CFC9DFCA5FCD5" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Kroyer" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[717,837,794,820]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Pomatoschistus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microps">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F66FFF1FD2CFC9DFD3EFCD5" box="[717,734,795,820]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F66FFF1FD0DFC9DFCA5FCD5" box="[748,837,795,820]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">microps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F66FFF1FF26FCB8FB93FC9C" blockId="83.[151,1437,290,964]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
Habitat. Inhabits silty sand or mud bottom, generally at depths of less than 
<specimenCount id="FFC9FD543F66FFF1FBECFCB8FBDEFCB9" box="[1037,1086,830,856]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" type="generic">
<quantity id="2E379B383F66FFF1FBECFCB8FBDAFCB9" box="[1037,1082,830,856]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
Able to quickly bury itself into the sediment to level of eyes; tolerates a wide range of salinities (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F66FFF1FC93FCE4FB87FC9C" author="Miller, P. J. &amp; Fouda, M. M." box="[882,1127,866,893]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="395 - 409" refId="ref61823" refString="Miller, P. J. &amp; Fouda, M. M. (1986) Notes on the biology of a Red Sea goby, Silhouettea aegyptia (Chabanaud, 1933) (Teleostei: Gobiidae). Cybium, Paris, 10 (4), 395 - 409." type="journal article" year="1986">Miller &amp; Fouda 1986</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F66FFF1FF26FC00FB60FC25" blockId="83.[151,1437,290,964]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
Geographic distribution. Originally restricted to the Red Sea. In the Mediterranean, it has been recorded from Ashdod and Bardawil Lagoon (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F66FFF1FE17FC2CFD0AFC25" author="Miller, P. J. &amp; Fouda, M. M." box="[502,746,938,964]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="395 - 409" refId="ref61823" refString="Miller, P. J. &amp; Fouda, M. M. (1986) Notes on the biology of a Red Sea goby, Silhouettea aegyptia (Chabanaud, 1933) (Teleostei: Gobiidae). Cybium, Paris, 10 (4), 395 - 409." type="journal article" year="1986">Miller &amp; Fouda 1986</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F66FFF1FD17FC2CFC62FC25" author="Golani, D." box="[758,898,938,964]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="1 - 108" refId="ref55342" refString="Golani, D. (2021) An updated checklist of the Mediterranean fishes of Israel, with illustrations of recently recorded species and delineation of Lessepsian migrants. Zootaxa, 4956 (1), 1 - 108. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4956.1.1" type="journal article" year="2021">Golani 2021</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F66FFF1FC20FC2CFC1CFC25" box="[961,1020,938,964]" name="Syria" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Syria</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F66FFF1FBEAFC2CFB94FC25" author="Ali, M." box="[1035,1140,938,964]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="388 - 393" refId="ref50790" refString="Ali, M. (2018) An updated Checklist of Marine fishes from Syria with an emphasis on alien species. Mediterranean Marine Science, 19 (2), 388 - 393. https: // doi. org / 10.12681 / mms. 15850" type="journal article" year="2018">Ali 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
